Otherwise, it computes the pseudo-inverse\n    and pseudo-determinant of A accounting only for positive and large-enough eigenvalues.\n\n    Parameters\n    ----------\n    A: numpy.array(dims=2)\n        The symmetric matrix.\n    b: numpy.array(dims=1)\n        The right-hand side of the linear equation.\n    eps: float, optional\n        Any eigenvalue smaller than eps*max_eigenval is ignored for the computation of the\n        pseudo-inverse.\n\n    Returns\n    -------\n    x: numpy.array(dims=1)\n        The solution of Ax=b.\n    log_det:\n        The (pseudo-)log-determinant of A.\n    ";

 0401:     """ Solve the linear system Ax=b and return x and the log-determinant of A for a
 0402:     symmetric matrix A that should be positive definite but might be close to singular
 0403:     or slightly non-positive.
 0404: 
 0405:     If A is symmteric positive, this function simply solves the linear system and computes
 0406:     the determinant using a Cholesky decomposition. Otherwise, it computes the pseudo-inverse
 0407:     and pseudo-determinant of A accounting only for positive and large-enough eigenvalues.
 0408: 
 0409:     Parameters
 0410:     ----------
 0411:     A: numpy.array(dims=2)
 0412:         The symmetric matrix.
 0413:     b: numpy.array(dims=1)
 0414:         The right-hand side of the linear equation.
 0415:     eps: float, optional
 0416:         Any eigenvalue smaller than eps*max_eigenval is ignored for the computation of the
 0417:         pseudo-inverse.
 0418: 
 0419:     Returns

 0421:     x: numpy.array(dims=1)
